5. prostibulum. This charge against Philumena, if not a figure of speech, is unsupported by any other authority, end may be set down to scandsl. Not even Tertullian alleges any criminality between herself and Apelles.

6. cuius energemate circumventus, ‘misled by whose influence': energema refers to the influence oi the evil spirit (ch. 6) with which Tertullian believed her to be possessed. The word recurs in the same connexion de cora. car. 24 ‘ad energema Apelleiacae virginis Philu- menes': comp. Hieronym. Commeat. in Gal. i. 8; Epist. 133. 4.

7. Phaneroseis scripsit. It appears from Ps.·Tert. odo. isaer. 6, that Apelles caused public lections to be read from this book of ‘Manifestations’ dictated by Philumena: scripsit=‘wrote at her dictation': comp. Hippol. ode. haer. x. 20.
